  "prompt": "How can you determine the Lewis structure of so3?",
  "response": "To determine the Lewis structure of sulfur trioxide (\\( \\text{SO}_3 \\)), you can follow these steps:\n\n1. **Count the total valence electrons**: \n   - Sulfur (\\( S \\) ) is in group 16 and has 6 valence electrons.\n   - Each oxygen (\\( O \\) ) is also in group 16 and has 6 valence electrons. Since there are three oxygen atoms, the total from oxygen is \\( 6 \\times 3 = 18 \\) electrons.\n   - Therefore, the total number of valence electrons in \\( \\text{SO}_3 \\) is \\( 6 (S) + 18 (O) = 24 \\) electrons.\n\n2. **Determine the central atom**: \n   - Sulfur is less electronegative than oxygen, so it will be the central atom in the Lewis structure.\n\n3. **Draw single bonds**: \n   - Connect the sulfur atom to each of the three oxygen atoms using single bonds. This uses up \\( 6 \\) electrons ( \\( 3 \\) bonds, each using \\( 2 \\) electrons).\n\n4. **Distribute remaining electrons**: \n   - After forming the bonds, you have \\( 24 - 6 = 18 \\) electrons remaining. \n   - Distribute the remaining electrons to satisfy the octet rule for the oxygen atoms. Place \\( 6 \\) electrons (or \\( 3 \\) lone pairs) around each of the three oxygen atoms. This uses another \\( 18 \\) electrons, so now all \\( 24 \\) electrons are accounted for.\n\n5. **Check the octet rule**: \n   - Each oxygen atom has 8 electrons (6 from lone pairs, 2 from the bonds).\n   - However, sulfur only has \\( 6 \\) electrons around it (from the single bonds). To give sulfur a complete octet, we can convert lone pairs on oxygen to double bonds. \n\n6. **Form double bonds**: \n   - Convert one lone pair from each of the oxygen atoms into a double bond with the sulfur atom. This gives you three double bonds ( \\( S=O \\) ) and allows sulfur to have \\( 12 \\) electrons around it, satisfying its ability to accommodate more than 8 electrons due to its position in period 3.\n\n7. **Final structure**: \n   - The resulting Lewis structure for \\( \\text{SO}_3 \\) shows sulfur in the center with three double bonds connecting to three oxygen atoms. Each oxygen has no lone pairs left in this structure.\n\nThe final Lewis structure can be represented as:\n\n```\n     O\n     ||\n O = S = O\n     ||\n     O\n```\n\nIn this structure, sulfur follows the expanded octet rule with 12 electrons, and each oxygen atom has 8 electrons, thus satisfying the octet rule.",
